  "response": "China has repeatedly blocked India's efforts to designate Masood Azhar, the chief of Jaish-e-Mohammed (JeM), as a global terrorist at the UN Security Council's 1267 Sanctions Committee. Their objections have been primarily based on diplomatic and strategic considerations:\n\n1. Diplomatic protection of Pakistan: China considers Pakistan a close ally and does not want to embarrass or put diplomatic pressure on its strategic partner.\n\n2. Technical grounds: China has argued that the evidence against Masood Azhar does not meet the technical requirements for designation as a global terrorist.\n\n3. Geopolitical considerations: China wants to maintain its strategic relationship with Pakistan and does not want to be seen as taking sides in the India-Pakistan conflict.\n\n4. Protecting regional stability: China claims that unilateral designations might escalate tensions between India and Pakistan.\n\nAfter years of blocking, China finally agreed to list Masood Azhar as a global terrorist in May 2019, following international pressure and after the Pulwama terror attack in Kashmir. However, the historical pattern of objections was driven by these strategic and diplomatic calculations.\n\nThe specific reasons for each objection might vary, but these were the general underlying factors in China's previous stance.",
